{
  "id": "networkx_networkx_8531",
  "repo_name": "networkx/networkx",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/networkx/networkx",
  "base_commit": "991fbe966a7af0ebd74d5929966b468a602c9c59",
  "pr_number": 8531,
  "issue_number": 8523,
  "issue_title": "min_weighted_dominating_set implementation problem",
  "issue_body": "<!-- If you have a general question about NetworkX, please use the discussions tab to create a new discussion -->\n\n<!--- Provide a general summary of the issue in the Title above -->\n\n### Current Behavior\n\n<!--- Tell us what happens instead of the expected behavior -->\nFirst of all, I would like to clarify that I am in no way an expert in the subject, so its possible that I am misunderstanding something.\nI have a network (with unweighted vertices) that is highly connected and I needed the dominating set. I tried both functions available in networkx for this purpose. I expected that [min_weighted_dominating_set](https://networkx.org/documentation/stable/reference/algorithms/generated/networkx.algorithms.approximation.dominating_set.min_weighted_dominating_set.html#min-weighted-dominating-set) would get a set with at most the same number of members than [dominating_set](https://networkx.org/documentation/stable/reference/algorithms/generated/networkx.algorithms.dominating.dominating_set.html#dominating-set) since the last one just adds arbitrary nodes from the remaning nodes, but in my use case this was not the case.\n\na toy example:\n```python3\nimport networkx as nx\ngraph = nx.complete_graph(5)\ngraph.add_edge(4, 5)\ngraph.add_edge(5, 6)\nprint(nx.algorithms.dominating_set(graph)) # {0, 5}\nprint(nx.algorithms.approximation.min_weighted_dominating_set(graph)) # {0, 1, 2, 4, 5}\n```\nI think that the problem is that in this line:\nhttps://github.com/networkx/networkx/blob/c2bb296ad5d8d821463d10cf09911dbafff7ca1b/networkx/algorithms/approximation/dominating_set.py#L92\nwe are substracting only `dom_set`, but the neighbors of the `dom_set` should also be substracted\n\n### Expected Behavior\n\n<!--- Tell us what should happen -->\nAn alternative that I am using is to calculate the intersection between `neighborhood` and `vertices` (the undominated nodes):\n```python3\n    def _cost(node_and_neighborhood):\n        \"\"\"Returns the cost-effectiveness of greedily choosing the given\n        node.\n\n        `node_and_neighborhood` is a two-tuple comprising a node and its\n        closed neighborhood.\n\n        \"\"\"\n        v, neighborhood = node_and_neighborhood\n        # return G.nodes[v].get(weight, 1) / len(neighborhood - dom_set)\n        length = len(neighborhood & vertices)\n        if length == 0:\n            return float(\"inf\")\n        return G.nodes[v].get(weight, 1) / length\n```\nwith this cost function the result in the example is `{4, 5}`. Selecting first the most connected node (4), and then adding 5 to dominate 6.  \n\n\n### Steps to Reproduce\n\n<!--- Provide a minimal example that reproduces the bug -->\n\n### Environment\n\n<!--- Please provide details about your local environment -->\n\nPython version: 3.13.12\nNetworkX version: 3.6.1\n\n### Additional context\n\n<!--- Add any other context about the problem here, screenshots, etc. -->\nWhile trying to understand the problem I read the cited reference (Vazirani, Vijay V. Approximation Algorithms. Springer Science & Business Media, 2001). However, I could not understand the algorithm described in there. Instead, I used this one:\nPotluri, A., & Singh, A. (2013). Hybrid metaheuristic algorithms for minimum weight dominating set. Applied Soft Computing, 13(1), 76\u201388. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.asoc.2012.07.009\nwhere it describes various cost function for the greedy algorithm, including this one (eq 1; it uses max instead of min). These are the relevant lines:\n\n> 4. Greedy heuristics for minimum weight dominating set\n> We experimented with four different variations of a greedy heuristic to determine the minimum weight dominating set. In every algorithm, initially all nodes are colored WHITE. A node that is included in the dominating set is colored BLACK, whereas all nodes adjacent to the dominating node are colored GREY. We halt the algorithm when no WHITE nodes exist in the graph.\n> In the first heuristic, we use an algorithm based on the standard greedy algorithm for the weighted set-cover problem [19]. The dominating set being constructed, D, is initialized to a NULL set in the beginning. The white degree of a node, d(u), is the number of WHITE neighbors of a given node u. For computing the minimum weight dominating set, we divide the white degree of the node, d(u), by the weight of the node w(u) and add the node with the maximum ratio to the dominating set D.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-02-24T22:37:51Z",
